title.text: H2H Employee Satisfaction and Clinical Supervision Rating Survey

pages.sub_heading: MHA of NYC wants to know how you feel about working here, and what we can do to improve your experience. Please take a few minutes to complete the following survey. Your responses will be deidentified, and we will only use aggregate data in our analyses; please be honest. We value your time and feedback.

questions.heading: I am between:
I have been employed at MHA for:
I have other employment outside MHA
I work outside of MHA in a clinical/therapeutic capacity:

pages.sub_heading: Answer the following questions based on the last 30 days. Answer the following questions ONLY if you provide crisis or intake counseling on any of the H2H lines. If you are not involved in providing services by phone, chat, and/or text, please skip to the next page.

questions.heading: I am happy.
I am preoccupied with more than one person I help.
I get satisfaction from being able to help people.
I feel connected to others.
I jump or am startled by unexpected sounds.
I feel invigorated after working with those I help.
I find it difficult to separate my personal life from my life as a counselor.
I am not as productive at work because I am losing sleep over traumatic experiences of a person I help.
I think that I might have been affected by the traumatic stress of those I help.
I feel trapped by my job as a counselor.
Because of my counseling, I have felt "on edge" about various things.
I like my work as a counselor.
I feel depressed because of the traumatic experiences of the people I help.
I feel as though I am experiencing the trauma of someone I have helped.
I have beliefs that sustain me.
I am pleased with how I am able to keep up with counseling techniques and protocols.
I am the person I always wanted to be.
My work makes me feel satisfied.
I feel worn out because of my work as a counselor.
I have happy thoughts and feelings about those I help and how I could help them.
I feel overwhelmed because my casework load seems endless.
I believe I can make a difference through my work.
I avoid certain activities or situations because they remind me of frightening experiences of the people I help.
I am proud of what I can do to help.
As a result of my helping I have intrusive, frightening thoughts.
I feel "bogged down" by the system.
I have thoughts that I am a "success" as a counselor.
I can't recall important parts of my work with trauma victims.
I am a very caring person.
I am happy that I chose to do this work.

pages.heading: Counselor Satisfaction Survey

pages.sub_heading: The following questions are for ALL H2H employees. Please answer these questions even if you do not provide crisis or intake counseling services by phone, chat, and/or text.

questions.heading: I am fairly compensated.
I am happy with my work shift.
I am learning from my peers.
I am learning from my supervisor(s).
I have opportunities for growth within the organization.
I have opportunities for professional development.

pages.heading: Answer the following questions in general, not only based on the last 30 days

pages.sub_heading: MHA of NYC wants to know how you feel about clinical supervision, and what we can do to improve your experience. Please take a few minutes to complete the following survey. Your responses will be deidentified, and we will only use aggregate data in our analyses; please be honest. Please complete these questions for each of your supervisors, separately. We value your time and feedback.

answers.text: I do not receive clinical supervision (Skip to Next Page)

questions.heading: I receive individual clinical supervision with:
My supervisor was approachable
My supervisor was respectful of my views and ideas
My supervisor gave me feedback in a way that felt safe
My supervisor was enthusiastic about supervising me
I felt able to openly discuss my concerns with my supervisor
My supervisor was non-judgemental in supervision
My supervisor was open-minded in supervision
My supervisor gave me positive feedback on my performance
My supervisor had a collaborative approach in supervision
My supervisor encouraged me to reflect on my practice
My supervisor paid attention to my unspoken feelings and anxieties
My supervisor drew flexibly from a number of theoretical models
My supervisor paid close attention to the process of supervision
My supervisor helped me identify my own learning/training needs
Supervision sessions were focused
Supervision sessions were structured
My supervision sessions were disorganised
My supervisor made sure that our supervision sessions were kept free from interruptions
